Note:
Regex Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the regex translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    regex source
      -> regex_lexer    (tokenize: literals, escapes, char classes, shorthand
                         classes, quantifiers incl. lazy/possessive, anchors,
                         groups incl. named + lookaround, alternation, backref)
      -> regex_parser   (build the regex AST: alternation of concatenations of
                         quantified atoms, groups, classes, anchors, backrefs)
      -> regex_to_hir   (lower the AST to the dict/list-encoded HIR interchange)
      -> hir_to_regex   (emit HIR back to a valid PCRE pattern string)
      -> re-lex / re-parse / re-to_hir of the emitted text
      -> structural + content assertions on the key constructs

The probe feeds a representative pattern that exercises every construct the
task requires:

  - literal characters and concatenation        (abc, def, foo, x)
  - a character class with a range               ([a-z0-9])
  - a shorthand class                            (\d)
  - a bounded quantifier {n,m}                   ({2,5})
  - a lazy quantifier                            (x*?)
  - anchors                                      (^, $, \b)
  - a capturing group                            ((abc|def|ghi))
  - a named group                                ((?<year>...))
  - an alternation with >= 2 alternatives        (abc|def|ghi)
  - a positive lookahead                         ((?=foo))
  - a backreference                              (\1)

The regex HIR node model is the dict/list-encoded interchange shared by
regex_to_hir (producer) and hir_to_regex (consumer): each node is a Dict
primitive keyed by a "type" tag plus per-kind payload keys ("branches",
"elements", "quantifier", "element", "group_type", "name", "contents",
"value"). This probe reads HIR fields through the exact Dict/List primitives
the producer and consumer use, so the test exercises the real contract.

It lowers the source to HIR1, asserts HIR1 is a "regex_pattern" carrying a
"pattern" body, emits HIR1 back to a PCRE string, asserts the emitted text
carries the load-bearing tokens of every required construct (whitespace-free,
so token presence is a faithful content check), re-runs the whole pipeline on
the emitted text to HIR2, and asserts HIR2 is a regex_pattern as well. A
second pass walks HIR2 structurally to confirm the alternation, named group,
quantifiers, char class, anchors, lookahead and backreference node kinds
survive the round trip.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/regex/regex_to_hir.runa" as RegexFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/regex/hir_to_regex.runa" as RegexBackend
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR dict/list readers (use the same primitives the pipeline uses)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Regex HIR nodes are Dict primitives keyed by null-terminated string literals.
Looking up a value means building a fresh key string with the same content and
calling Dict.get, which compares keys by content via the hashtable. This mirror
of the producer's key construction proves the produced shape is the consumed
shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_get" takes node as Integer, key_literal as String returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key_literal
    Return proc get from Dict with node, key
End Process

@Reasoning:
A regex HIR node's kind is the string value stored under "type"; returning it
lets callers compare against an expected tag with string_equals.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_type" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc hir_get with node, "type"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience predicate: does a node carry the given "type" tag? Returns 1 on a
content match, 0 otherwise (including a null node or missing type).
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_is_type" takes node as Integer, expected as String returns Integer:
    Let t be proc hir_type with node
    If t is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc string_equals from StringCore with t, expected
End Process

@Reasoning:
The pattern body lives under the root's "pattern" key. Unwrapping it here keeps
the assertions focused on the meaningful expression node rather than the
envelope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_pattern_body" takes root as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc hir_get with root, "pattern"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "Regex translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative pattern exercising: start anchor, named group around a
    shorthand class with a bounded quantifier, a capturing group holding a
    3-way alternation, a char class with a range and a '+' quantifier, a lazy
    quantifier, a positive lookahead, a backreference, a word-boundary anchor,
    and an end anchor.
    :End Note
    Let source be "^(?<year>\\d{2,5})(abc|def|ghi)[a-z0-9]+x*?(?=foo)\\1\\b$"

    Note: --- Stage 0-2: source -> HIR1 ---
    Let hir1 be proc regex_to_hir_from_source from RegexFrontend with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "frontend produced HIR", hir1

    Let root_is_pattern be proc hir_is_type with hir1, "regex_pattern"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR root is a regex_pattern", root_is_pattern, 1

    Let body1 be proc hir_pattern_body with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pattern body present", body1

    Note:
    The top-level body is a concatenation of the anchors, groups, class and
    backreference. Confirm the body is a concatenation with several elements.
    :End Note
    Let body_is_concat be proc hir_is_type with body1, "concatenation"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "body is a concatenation", body_is_concat, 1
    Let elements be proc hir_get with body1, "elements"
    Let element_count be proc size from List with elements
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "concatenation has several elements", element_count, 6

    Note: --- Stage 3: HIR1 -> regex text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_regex_from_hir from RegexBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced regex text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted regex is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note:
    --- Depth assertions: the emitted text must carry the load-bearing tokens
    of every required construct. The output is whitespace-free, so substring
    presence is a faithful content check that each construct survived.
    :End Note
    Let has_class_range be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "[a-z0-9]"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries char class with range", has_class_range, 1
    Let has_shorthand be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "\\d"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries shorthand class", has_shorthand, 1
    Let has_range_quant be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "{2,5}"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries {n,m} quantifier", has_range_quant, 1
    Let has_lazy be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "*?"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries lazy quantifier", has_lazy, 1
    Let has_anchor_start be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "^"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries start anchor", has_anchor_start, 1
    Let has_anchor_end be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "$"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries end anchor", has_anchor_end, 1
    Let has_word_boundary be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "\\b"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries word-boundary anchor", has_word_boundary, 1
    Let has_capturing be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "(abc"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries capturing group", has_capturing, 1
    Let has_named be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "(?<year>"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries named group", has_named, 1
    Let has_alt be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "abc|def|ghi"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries alternation with >= 2 alts", has_alt, 1
    Let has_lookahead be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "(?=foo)"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries lookahead", has_lookahead, 1
    Let has_backref be proc string_contains from StringUtils with emitted, "\\1"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "emitted carries backreference", has_backref, 1

    Note: --- Stage 4: re-run the pipeline on the emitted text -> HIR2 ---
    Let hir2 be proc regex_to_hir_from_source from RegexFrontend with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted regex produced HIR", hir2
    Let root2_is_pattern be proc hir_is_type with hir2, "regex_pattern"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip root is a regex_pattern", root2_is_pattern, 1

    Let body2 be proc hir_pattern_body with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip pattern body present", body2
    Let body2_is_concat be proc hir_is_type with body2, "concatenation"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip body is a concatenation", body2_is_concat, 1

    Note:
    --- Structural depth walk on HIR2: locate each required node kind inside the
    re-parsed tree, proving the constructs survived as structure (not just text).
    :End Note
    Let elements2 be proc hir_get with body2, "elements"
    Let element2_count be proc size from List with elements2
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip concatenation has several elements", element2_count, 6

    Note: Find the named group, the capturing group (with alternation), the
    Note: quantified char-class, the lazy-quantified atom, the lookahead group,
    Note: the anchors and the backreference among the concatenation elements.
    Let found_named be 0
    Let found_capturing_alt be 0
    Let found_quant_class be 0
    Let found_lazy be 0
    Let found_lookahead be 0
    Let found_anchor be 0
    Let found_backref be 0

    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than element2_count:
        Let elem be proc get from List with elements2, idx

        Let is_group be proc hir_is_type with elem, "group"
        If is_group is equal to 1:
            Let gtype be proc hir_get with elem, "group_type"
            If gtype is not equal to 0:
                Let is_named_g be proc string_equals from StringCore with gtype, "named"
                If is_named_g is equal to 1:
                    Set found_named to 1
                End If
                Let is_lah_g be proc string_equals from StringCore with gtype, "lookahead_pos"
                If is_lah_g is equal to 1:
                    Set found_lookahead to 1
                End If
                Let is_cap_g be proc string_equals from StringCore with gtype, "capturing"
                If is_cap_g is equal to 1:
                    Let gcontents be proc hir_get with elem, "contents"
                    Let contents_is_alt be proc hir_is_type with gcontents, "alternation"
                    If contents_is_alt is equal to 1:
                        Set found_capturing_alt to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Let is_quant be proc hir_is_type with elem, "quantified"
        If is_quant is equal to 1:
            Let q be proc hir_get with elem, "quantifier"
            If q is not equal to 0:
                Let q_is_lazy be proc string_equals from StringCore with q, "*?"
                If q_is_lazy is equal to 1:
                    Set found_lazy to 1
                End If
            End If
            Let qelem be proc hir_get with elem, "element"
            Let qelem_is_class be proc hir_is_type with qelem, "char_class"
            If qelem_is_class is equal to 1:
                Set found_quant_class to 1
            End If
        End If

        Let is_anchor be proc hir_is_type with elem, "anchor"
        If is_anchor is equal to 1:
            Set found_anchor to 1
        End If

        Let is_backref be proc hir_is_type with elem, "backreference"
        If is_backref is equal to 1:
            Set found_backref to 1
        End If

        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves named group node", found_named, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves capturing group with alternation", found_capturing_alt, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves quantified char class", found_quant_class, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves lazy quantifier", found_lazy, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves lookahead group", found_lookahead, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves an anchor", found_anchor, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves backreference", found_backref, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
